 United Kingdom; Lister Hospital, United Kingdom; Luton And Dunstable Hospital, United Kingdom; Macclesfield District General Hospital, United Kingdom; Morriston Hospital, United Kingdom; NHS Ayrshire, United Kingdom; NHS Grampian, United Kingdom; Ninewells Hospital, NHS, United Kingdom; Norfolk And Norwich University Hospital, United Kingdom; North Bristol NHS Trust, United Kingdom; North Devon District Hospital, United Kingdom; Northwick Park Hospital, United Kingdom; Nottingham Children’s Hospital At Queens Medical Centre Campus, United Kingdom; Oxford University Hospitals, United Kingdom; Perth Royal Infirmary, United Kingdom; Plymouth Hospitals NHS Trust, United Kingdom; Princess Alexandra Hospital, United Kingdom; Princess Of Wales Hospital, United Kingdom; Queen Elizabeth Hospital Woolwich, United Kingdom; Queen Elizabeth Hospital Birmingham, United Kingdom; Queen Elizabeth Hospital King’s Lynn, United Kingdom; Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother Hospital, United Kingdom; Raigmore Hospital, United Kingdom; Royal Alexandria Hospital, United Kingdom; Royal Bolton Hospital, United Kingdom; Royal Derby Hospital, United Kingdom; Royal Devon And Exeter National Health Service Foundation Trust, United Kingdom; Royal Devon & Exeter NHS Foundation Trust, United Kingdom; Royal Free Hospital, United Kingdom; Royal Glamorgan Hospital, United Kingdom; Royal Gwent Hospital, United Kingdom; Royal Hospital For Sick Children, United Kingdom; Royal Infirmary Of Edinburgh, United Kingdom; Royal London Hospital, United Kingdom; Royal United Hospital Bath, United Kingdom; Salford Royal NHS Foundation Trust, United Kingdom; Sandwell And West Birmingham Hospitals NHS Trust, United Kingdom; Sheffield Children’s Hospital, United Kingdom; Sheffield Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, United Kingdom; Sherwood Forest Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust, United Kingdom; Southend University Hospital, United Kingdom; Southern General Hospital, United Kingdom; Southmead Hospital, United Kingdom; Southmead Hospital, North Bristol NHS Trust, United Kingdom; St Georges Healthcare NHS Trust, United Kingdom; St.George’s Healthcare NHS Trust And University, United Kingdom; St. James’s University Hospital, United Kingdom; St Mary’s Hospital, United Kingdom; Stockport NHS Foundation Trust, United Kingdom; St Thomas’ Hospital, United Kingdom; The Royal Gwent Hospital, United Kingdom; The Royal Infirmary Of Edinburgh, United Kingdom; The University Hospital Of South Manchester, United Kingdom; United Lincolnshire Hospitals Pilgrim Hospital, United Kingdom; University Hospital Coventry And Warwickshire, United Kingdom; University Hospital Of North Midlands, United Kingdom; University Hospital Of North Staffordshire NHS Trust, United Kingdom; University Hospital Of Wales, United Kingdom; University Hospitals Leicester Leicester Royal Infirmary, United Kingdom; Watford General Hospital, United Kingdom; Western General Hospital, United Kingdom; Western Sussex Hospitals NHS Trust, United Kingdom; Weston General Hospital, United Kingdom; Whipps Cross University Hospital, United Kingdom; Wishaw General Hospital, United Kingdom; Wrexham Maelor Hospital, United Kingdom; Yeovil District Hospital, United Kingdom; Massachusetts General Hospital, United States; Medstar Washington Hospital Center, United States; Northwestern Memorial Hospital, United States; The Rhode Island Hospital, United States; Thomas Jefferson University Hospital, United States; Tufts Medical Center, United States; University of Pittsburgh Medical Center Presbyterian Hospital, United States; University of Michigan, United States; St Francis Hospital, Zambia; NIHR Unit on Global Surgery (Universities of Birmingham, Edinburgh and Warwick), University of Edinburgh, Royal Infirmary of Edinburgh, Edinburgh, EH16 4SA, United Kingdom},
	abstract = {Background: Appendicitis is the most common abdominal surgical emergency worldwide. Differences between high- and low-income settings in the availability of laparoscopic appendectomy, alternative management choices, and outcomes are poorly described. The aim was to identify variation in surgical management and outcomes of appendicitis within low-, middle-, and high-Human Development Index (HDI) countries worldwide. Methods: This is a multicenter, international prospective cohort study. Consecutive sampling of patients undergoing emergency appendectomy over 6 months was conducted. Follow-up lasted 30 days. Results: 4546 patients from 52 countries underwent appendectomy (2499 high-, 1540 middle-, and 507 low-HDI groups). Surgical site infection (SSI) rates were higher in low-HDI (OR 2.57, 95% CI 1.33–4.99, p = 0.005) but not middle-HDI countries (OR 1.38, 95% CI 0.76–2.52, p = 0.291), compared with high-HDI countries after adjustment. A laparoscopic approach was common in high-HDI countries (1693/2499, 67.7%), but infrequent in low-HDI (41/507, 8.1%) and middle-HDI (132/1540, 8.6%) groups. After accounting for case-mix, laparoscopy was still associated with fewer overall complications (OR 0.55, 95% CI 0.42–0.71, p < 0.001) and SSIs (OR 0.22, 95% CI 0.14–0.33, p < 0.001). In propensity-score matched groups within low-/middle-HDI countries, laparoscopy was still associated with fewer overall complications (OR 0.23 95% CI 0.11–0.44) and SSI (OR 0.21 95% CI 0.09–0.45). Conclusion: A laparoscopic approach is associated with better outcomes and availability appears to differ by country HDI. Despite the profound clinical, operational, and financial barriers to its widespread introduction, laparoscopy could significantly improve outcomes for patients in low-resource environments. Trial registration: NCT02179112. © 2018, The Author(s).},
