	affiliations = {Hepatology and Liver Transplant Unit, Hospital Universitario Austral, Pilar, Argentina; Latin American Liver Research Educational and Awareness Network (LALREAN); Liver Section, Centro de Educación Médica e Investigaciones Clínicas, Buenos Aires, Argentina; Hepatology and Liver Transplant Unit, Hospital Alemán, Buenos Aires, Argentina; Department of Internal Medicine, Sanatorio Anchorena, Buenos Aires, Argentina; Department of Internal Medicine, Centro Médico ABC, Ciudad de México, Mexico; Gastroenterology Unit, Hospital Nacional Daniel A. Carrión, Callao, Peru; Gastroenterology Section, Internal Medicine Department, Hospital Clínico de la Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Hepatology and Liver Transplant Unit, Hospitales de San Vicente Fundación de Medellín y Rionegro, Medellín, Colombia; Hospital Nacional Edgardo Rebagliati Martins, Lima, Peru; Department of Gastroenterology, Hospital de Clínicas José de San Martín, Universidad de Buenos Aires, Buenos Aires, Argentina; Department of Gastroenterology, Instituto Nacional de Ciencias Médicas y Nutrición, Ciudad de México, Mexico; Intensive Care Unit, Hospital de Infecciosas Francisco J Muñiz, Buenos Aires, Argentina; Hospital Especializado en Enfermedades Infecciosas Instituto Couto Maia, Salvador de Bahía, Brazil; Gastroenterology Unit, Hospital Nacional Guillermo Almenara Irigoyen, Lima, Peru; Liver Unit, Fundación Cardio-Infantil, Bogotá, Colombia; Hospital Regional Dr. Teodoro Maldonado Carbo del IESS, Guayaquil, Ecuador; Gastroenterology Unit, Clínica Anglo-Americana, Lima, Peru; Gastroenterology Unit, Hospital de Víctor Lazarte Echegaray, Trujillo, Peru; Gastroenterology Unit, Clínica Delgado, Lima, Peru; Gastroenterology Unit, Hospital Nacional Almanzor Aguinaga Asenjo, Chiclayo, Peru; Department of Medicine, IMSS Hospital General Regional No.1 “Dr. Carlos Mc Gregor Sánchez”, Ciudad de México, Mexico; Department of Gastroenterology and Hepatology, Hospital General de México “Dr. Eduardo Liceaga”, Ciudad de México, Mexico; Endoscopy and Transplant Service, Hospital Universitario Fundación Santa Fé de Bogotá, Bogotá, Colombia; Department of Gastroenterology, Hospital Padre Hurtado, Santiago, Chile; Gastroenterology Unit, Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional La Raza IMSS, Ciudad de México, Mexico; Department of Gastroenterology, CEDIMAT, Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic; Department of Gastroenterology, Hospital Alianza, Bahía, Brazil; Gastroenterology Unit, Hospital Valdivia, Universidad Austral de Chile, Valdivia, Chile; Department of Gastroenterology, Hospital de Clínicas, Universidad Nacional de Asunción, Asunción, Paraguay; Hepatology and Liver Transplant Unit, Hospital Central De las Fuerzas Armadas, Montevideo, Uruguay; Department of Gastroenterology, Hospital Roosevelt, Ciudad de Guatemala, Guatemala; Department of Gastroenterology, Hospital Provincial del Centenario, Rosario, Argentina; Instituto de Efectividad Clínica y Sanitaria, Buenos Aires, Argentina},
	abstract = {Introduction & objectives: The independent effect of liver biochemistries as a prognostic factor in patients with COVID-19 has not been completely addressed. We aimed to evaluate the prognostic value of abnormal liver tests on admission of hospitalized patients with COVID-19. Materials & methods: We performed a prospective cohort study including 1611 hospitalized patients with confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection from April 15, 2020 through July 31, 2020 in 38 different Hospitals from 11 Latin American countries. We registered clinical and laboratory parameters, including liver function tests, on admission and during hospitalization. All patients were followed until discharge or death. We fit multivariable logistic regression models, further post-estimation effect through margins and inverse probability weighting. Results: Overall, 57.8% of the patients were male with a mean age of 52.3 years, 8.5% had chronic liver disease and 3.4% had cirrhosis. Abnormal liver tests on admission were present on 45.2% (CI 42.7–47.7) of the cohort (n = 726). Overall, 15.1% (CI 13.4–16.9) of patients died (n = 244). Patients with abnormal liver tests on admission presented higher mortality 18.7% (CI 15.9–21.7), compared to those with normal liver biochemistries 12.2% (CI 10.1–14.6); P <.0001). After excluding patients with history of chronic liver disease, abnormal liver tests on admission were independently associated with death [OR 1.5 (CI 1.1–2.0); P = 0.01], and severe COVID-19 (2.6 [2.0–3.3], P <.0001), both adjusted by age, gender, diabetes, pneumonia and body mass index >30. Conclusions: The presence of abnormal liver tests on admission is independently associated with mortality and severe COVID-19 in hospitalized patients with COVID-19 infection and may be used as surrogate marker of inflammation. Clinicaltrials.gov: NCT04358380. © 2020 Fundación Clínica Médica Sur, A.C.},
	author_keywords = {Coronavirus; Death; Hepatitis; Pandemic; SARS-CoV-2},
	keywords = {Comorbidity; COVID-19; Female; Hospitalization; Humans; Latin America; Liver Diseases; Liver Function Tests; Male; Middle Aged; Prospective Studies; Risk Factors; SARS-CoV-2; alanine aminotransferase; albumin; alkaline phosphatase; bilirubin; adult; age; aged; alanine aminotransferase blood level; albumin blood level; alkaline phosphatase blood level; Argentina; Article; bilirubin blood level; body mass; Brazil; Chile; chronic liver disease; clinical outcome; cohort analysis; Colombia; controlled study; coronavirus disease 2019; diabetes mellitus; disease severity; Dominican Republic; Ecuador; female; gender; Guatemala; hospital admission; hospital patient; hospitalization; human; international normalized ratio; liver cirrhosis; liver function test; lymphocyte count; major clinical study; male; Mexico; mortality; mortality rate; mortality risk; obesity; Paraguay; Peru; platelet count; pneumonia; prognosis; prospective study; Uruguay; clinical trial; comorbidity; liver disease; liver function test; middle aged; multicenter study; risk factor; South and Central America},
