s Hospital Västerås, Sweden; Buergerspital Solothurn, Switzerland; Gzo Spital Wetzikon, Switzerland; Hospital Davos, Switzerland; Hopital Cochin, APHP, France; Baptist Medical Centre, Ghana; Acibadem University School of Medicine, Atakent Hospital, Turkey; Bagcilar Research and Training Hospital, Turkey; Bakirkoy Dr. Sadi Konuk Training and Research Hospital, Turkey; Karadeniz Technical University Faculty of Medicine, Turkey; Okmeydani Training and Research Hospital, Turkey; John Peter Smith Hospital, United States; CHU Saint Etienne, France; Blackpool Victoria Hospital, United Kingdom; Borders General Hospital, United Kingdom; CHU Nice, France; Darlington Memorial Hospital, United Kingdom; Gloucestershire Royal Hospital, United Kingdom; Kasr Al Ainy Faculty of Medicine, Cairo University, Egypt; Guy's and St. Thomas' Hospitals, United Kingdom; Heartlands Hospital, United Kingdom; Simplemente Evita, Argentina; John Radcliffe Hospital, Oxford, United Kingdom; Kettering General Hospital NHS Trust, United Kingdom; Hospital Lagomaggiore, Argentina; Maidstone & Tunbridge Wells NHS Trust, United Kingdom; Maistone and Tunbridge Wells NHS Trust, United Kingdom; Nevill Hall Hospital, United Kingdom; Ninewells Hospital, United Kingdom; St Francis Mission Hospital, Zambia; North Middlesex University Hospital, United Kingdom; Northampton General Hospital, United Kingdom; Nottingham University Hospital NHS Trust, United Kingdom; Ndola Central Hospital, Zambia; Pilgrim Hospital, United Lincolnshire Hospitals NHS Trust, United Kingdom; Queen Elizabeth University Hospital, Glasgow, United Kingdom; Queen's Hospital, BHR University Hospitals NHS Trust, United Kingdom; University of Pittsburgh Medical Center - Presbyterian, United States; Royal Alexandra Hospital, Paisley, United Kingdom; University of Michigan Medical Center, United States; Royal Devon & Exeter Hospital, United Kingdom; Northwestern Memorial Hospital, Northwestern University, United States; Rush University Medical Centre, United States; St George's Hospital, United Kingdom; New York Presbyterian Hospital, Columbia University Medical Center, United States; The Royal London Hospital, United Kingdom; Ulster Hospital Dundonald, United Kingdom; University Hospital Ayr, United Kingdom; University Hospital, United Kingdom; University Hospitals Birmingham NHS Trust, United Kingdom; Victoria Hospital Kirkcaldy, United Kingdom; Walsall Manor Hospital, Walsall, United Kingdom; Department of Clinical Surgery, University of Edinburgh, 51 Little France Crescent, Edinburgh, EH16 4SA, United Kingdom},
	abstract = {Background: Identification of patients at high risk of surgical-site infections may allow surgeons to minimize associated morbidity. However, there are significant concerns regarding the methodological quality and transportability of models previously developed. The aim of this study was to develop a novel score to predict 30-day surgical-site infection risk after gastrointestinal surgery across a global context and externally validate against existing models. Methods: This was a secondary analysis of two prospective international cohort studies: GlobalSurg-1 (July-November 2014) and GlobalSurg-2 (January-July 2016). Consecutive adults undergoing gastrointestinal surgery were eligible. Model development was performed using GlobalSurg-2 data, with novel and previous scores externally validated using GlobalSurg-1 data. The primary outcome was 30-day surgical-site infections, with two predictive techniques explored: penalized regression (least absolute shrinkage and selection operator ('LASSO')) and machine learning (extreme gradient boosting ('XGBoost')). Final model selection was based on prognostic accuracy and clinical utility. Results: There were 14 019 patients (surgical-site infections = 12.3%) for derivation and 8464 patients (surgical-site infections = 11.4%) for external validation. The LASSO model was selected due to similar discrimination to extreme gradient boosting (AUC 0.738 (95% c.i. 0.725 to 0.750) versus 0.737 (95% c.i. 0.709 to 0.765)), but greater explainability. The final score included six variables: country income, ASA grade, diabetes, and operative contamination, approach, and duration. Model performance remained good on external validation (AUC 0.730 (95% c.i. 0.715 to 0.744); calibration intercept -0.098 and slope 1.008) and demonstrated superior performance to the external validation of all previous models. Conclusion: The 'Global Surgical-Site Infection' score allows accurate prediction of the risk of surgical-site infections with six simple variables that are routinely available at the time of surgery across global settings. This can inform the use of intraoperative and postoperative interventions to modify the risk of surgical-site infections and minimize associated harm. © The Author(s) 2024. Published by Oxford University Press on behalf of BJS Foundation Ltd.},
	keywords = {acetylsalicylic acid; antibiotic agent; corticosteroid; immunosuppressive agent; adult; area under the curve; Article; calibration; chemotherapy; colostomy; comorbidity; contamination; development; diabetes mellitus; female; follow up; gastrointestinal surgery; human; Human immunodeficiency virus; human tissue; ileostomy; infection risk; insulin dependent diabetes mellitus; laparoscopy; laparotomy; least absolute shrinkage and selection operator; lossless compression; machine learning; malaria; male; non insulin dependent diabetes mellitus; pathology; perforation; predictive value; prospective study; risk; sensitivity analysis; smoking; surgical infection; systematic review; upper gastrointestinal bleeding; urgency status},
	correspondence_address = {E.M. Harrison; Department of Clinical Surgery, University of Edinburgh, Edinburgh, 51 Little France Crescent, EH16 4SA, United Kingdom; email: Ewen.Harrison@ed.ac.uk},
	publisher = {Oxford University Press},
