	affiliations = {Faculty of Health Sciences, Private University of Tacna, Tacna, Peru; Department of Medicine, Hospital III Daniel Alcides Carrión, Tacna, Peru; Roe Clinical Laboratory, Lima, Peru},
	abstract = {The rapid spread of SARS-CoV-2 and its variants worldwide has created a need for cheap, fast-performing diagnostic tests with broad population coverage that can screen for the identification and isolation of those infected. Pooling combines individual patient samples in a "block" and analyzes this pooling as an individual sample. If the pool test is negative, all individual samples are negative, but if the pool is positive, these samples should be tested individually. It has been shown that the pooling of respiratory samples (nasopharyngeal, oropharyngeal, or saliva swabs) for the diagnosis of SARS-CoV-2 can reduce the consumption of laboratory supplies and labor by up to 90% without affecting diagnostic performance. We review the main aspects, strategies, and results of pooling RT-PCR to diagnose SARS-CoV-2. © 2024 by Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.},
