	affiliations = {Research Group on Dynamics and Epidemiology of Antimicrobial Resistance—“One Health”, Universidad Cientifica del Sur, Lima, Peru; Microbiology Service, Instituto Nacional Materno Perinatal, Lima, Peru; Faculty of Health Sciences, Universidad Privada del Norte, Lima, Peru; Human Health School, Faculty of Health Sciences, Universidad Cientifica del Sur, Lima, Peru; Service of Infectious Diseases, Hospital Maria Auxiliadora, Lima, Peru; Laboratory of Microbiology, Hospital Nacional PNP Luis N. Sáenz, Lima, Peru; Center for Basic and Translational Research AUNA Ideas, Lima, Peru; Laboratory of Microbiology, Hospital Militar Central, Lima, Peru; Laboratory of Microbial Ecology, Universidad Nacional Mayor de San Marcos, Lima, Peru; Laboratory of Clinical Pathology, Hospital III Daniel Alcides Carrión, Tacna, Peru; Human Health School, Faculty of Health Sciences, Universidad Peruana Union (UPeU), Lima, Peru; Intensive Care Unit, Hospital Emergencias Ate Vitarte, Lima, Peru; Service of Infectious Diseases and Tropical Medicine, Hospital Regional de Loreto, Iquitos, Peru; Faculty of Human Medicine, Universidad Nacional de la Amazonia Peruana, Iquitos, Peru; Facuty of Health Sciences, Universidad de Huánuco, Huánuco, Peru; Molecular Microbiology Area, Center for Biomedical Research of La Rioja, Logroño, Spain},
	abstract = {Background: Common identification techniques do not differentiate among members of the Acinetobacter calcoaceticus–baumannii (ACB) complex, and the presence of non-baumannii Acinetobacter is often misinterpreted. The bla<sub>OXA−51</sub> gene is located within the chromosome of Acinetobacter baumannii. Despite its plasmid dissemination to other members of the genus, it may be considered in initial species screening. Thus, this study aimed to determine the presence of bla<sub>OXA−51</sub>-negative Acinetobacter spp. as a cause of infection in Peru. Methods: Two hundred ninety-eight ACB complex isolates from different regions of Peru were isolated between January 2018 and March 2024. Of these, 272 and 25 were confirmed as hospital-acquired and community infections, respectively. The presence of bla<sub>OXA−51</sub> was determined by polymerase chain reaction, and the susceptibility levels to 12 antimicrobial agents were determined. Results: The results showed that 38 (12.7%) isolates were bla<sub>OXA−51</sub>-negative. These isolates were frequent among community infections (13/25, p < 0.0001), often causing urine infections. They showed significantly lower levels of resistance to almost all antimicrobial agents tested, and most of them were recovered from regions outside metropolitan Lima. Conclusion: A relevant number of infections by non-baumannii Acinetobacter species in Peru is suggested, highlighting the need for systematic identification of these species in the country. Copyright © 2025 Rosario Oporto-Llerena et al. Journal of Tropical Medicine published by John Wiley & Sons Ltd.},
