esian Hospital, Gaza, Palestine; Allied Hospital, Faisalabad, Pakistan; Aga Khan University, Pakistan; Hospital Davos, Switzerland; King Edward Medical University, Mayo Hospital, Lahore, Pakistan; CMH Lahore Medical And Dental College, Pakistan; Nishtar Medical College And Hospital, Pakistan; Hospital de Clínicas, II Cátedra de Clínica Quirúrgica, Universidad Nacional de Asunción, Paraguay; Hospital Nacional Arzopispo Loayza, Peru; Hospital Cayetano Heredia, Peru; Clínica De Especialidades Médicas, Peru; Hospital Nacional Guillermo Almenara Irigoyen, Peru; Hospital Regional De Ayacucho, Peru; Hospital III José Cayetano Heredia, Peru; Hospital Nacional Maria Auxiliadora, Peru; Buergerspital Solothurn, Switzerland; The Medical City, Philippines; Department Of Surgery, Philippine General Hospital, University Of The Philippines Manila, Philippines; Department Of General, Oncological, Metabolic And Thoracic Surgery, Military Institute Of Medicine, Warsaw, Poland; Department Of Surgery, Jagiellonian University Medical College, Poland; Centro Hospitalar De São João, Portugal; Gzo Spital Wetzikon, Switzerland; Spital Judetean De Urgenta Din Craiova, Romania; Spitalul Clinic Judetean Brasov, Romania; Emergency Hospital of Bucharest, Romania; Umea University Hospital, Sweden; Kibungo Hospital, Rwanda; Karolinska Universitetssjukhuset, Solna, Sweden; Department of Surgery, Faculty of Medicine, King Abdulaziz University Hospital, Jeddah, Saudi Arabia; Department of Surgery, King Abdulaziz University Hospital, Oncology Center, Jeddah, Saudi Arabia; King Fahad Hospital, Jeddah, Saudi Arabia; King Fahad Medical City, Riyadh, Saudi Arabia; King Khaled University Hospital, Saudi Arabia; Clinic For General Surgery, Clinical Center Nis, Serbia; National University Hospital, Singapore; Victoria Hospital Wynberg, South Africa; Department Of Surgery, Department Of Clinical And Experimental Medicine, Linköping University, Norrköping, Sweden; Charlotte Maxeke Johannesburg Academic Hospital, South Africa; Västmanlands Hospital Västerås, Sweden; Tembisa Tertiary Provincial Hospital, South Africa; National Institute for Health Research Unit on Global Surgery, University of Birmingham, Institute of Translational Medicine, Heritage Building, Mindelsohn Way, Birmingham, B15 2TH, United Kingdom; New Somerset Hospital, South Africa; Helen Joseph Hospital, University Of Witwatersrand, South Africa; Stanger Hospital, South Africa; Mora Hospital, Sweden; Inkosi Albert Luthuli Central Hospital, South Africa; Mediclinic Potchefstroom, South Africa; Mitchell's Plain District Hospital, South Africa; Dr George Mukhari Academic Hospital, South Africa; Milpark Hospital, South Africa; University Hospital Rey Juan Carlos, Spain; Hospital Universitario San Agustín, Spain; Hospital Universitario de Getafe, Spain; Infanta Sofía University Hospital, Spain; Hospital Valle De Hebron, Spain; Central University Hospital Of Asturias, Spain},
	abstract = {Background: End colostomy rates following colorectal resection vary across institutions in high-income settings, being influenced by patient, disease, surgeon and system factors. This study aimed to assess global variation in end colostomy rates after left-sided colorectal resection. Methods: This study comprised an analysis of GlobalSurg-1 and-2 international, prospective, observational cohort studies (2014, 2016), including consecutive adult patients undergoing elective or emergency left-sided colorectal resection within discrete 2-week windows. Countries were grouped into high-, middle-and low-income tertiles according to the United Nations Human Development Index (HDI). Factors associated with colostomy formation versus primary anastomosis were explored using a multilevel, multivariable logistic regression model. Results: In total, 1635 patients from 242 hospitals in 57 countries undergoing left-sided colorectal resection were included: 113 (6·9 per cent) from low-HDI, 254 (15·5 per cent) from middle-HDI and 1268 (77·6 percent) from high-HDI countries. There was a higher proportion of patients with perforated disease (57·5, 40·9 and 35·4 per cent; P < 0·001) and subsequent use of end colostomy (52·2, 24·8 and 18·9 per cent; P < 0·001) in low-compared with middle-and high-HDI settings. The association with colostomy use in low-HDI settings persisted (odds ratio (OR) 3·20, 95 per cent c.i. 1·35 to 7·57; P = 0·008) after risk adjustment for malignant disease (OR 2·34, 1·65 to 3·32; P < 0·001), emergency surgery (OR 4·08, 2·73 to 6·10; P < 0·001), time to operation at least 48 h (OR 1·99, 1·28 to 3·09; P = 0·002) and disease perforation (OR 4·00, 2·81 to 5·69; P < 0·001). Conclusion: Global differences existed in the proportion of patients receiving end stomas after left-sided colorectal resection based on income, which went beyond case mix alone. © 2019 The Authors. BJS Open published by John Wiley & Sons Ltd on behalf of BJS Society Ltd.},
	keywords = {Adult; Aged; Aged, 80 and over; Anastomosis, Surgical; Colorectal Neoplasms; Colostomy; Developed Countries; Developing Countries; Elective Surgical Procedures; Emergencies; Female; Global Health; Humans; Logistic Models; Male; Middle Aged; Multivariate Analysis; Prospective Studies; adult; anastomosis; Article; case mix; cohort analysis; colorectal surgery; colostomy; disease association; elective surgery; emergency surgery; female; follow up; hemicolectomy; human; Human Development Index; information processing; laparoscopic surgery; major clinical study; male; middle aged; mortality; observational study; open surgery; outcome assessment; priority journal; prospective study; risk assessment; validation process; aged; anastomosis; clinical trial; colorectal tumor; colostomy; developing country; emergency; global health; multicenter study; multivariate analysis; statistical model; very elderly},
	correspondence_address = {A. Bhangu; National Institute for Health Research Unit on Global Surgery, University of Birmingham, Institute of Translational Medicine, Birmingham, Heritage Building Mindelsohn Way, B15 2TH, United Kingdom; email: a.a.bhangu@bham.ac.uk},
