niversity Hospital of Goettingen, Germany; University Hospital Jena, Greece; Charité, Germany; Fachkrankenhaus Coswig GmbH, Germany; Klinikum Forchheim, Germany; Hospital Victor Lazarte Echegaray, Peru; Hospital Nacional Carlos Alberto Seguin Escobedo, Peru; Clínica San Gabriel, Peru; HCFAP, Peru; Hospital Regional Docente, Peru; Foch, France; University Hospital of Brest, France; CHU Dijon, France; CHU Morvan, France; Hopital Cochin, France; Barzilai MC, Israel; Soroka Medical Center, Israel; Assuta Medical Center, Israel; Rambam Hospital, Israel; Shaare Zedek Medical Center, Israel; Astrid Lindgren Childerns Hospital, Switzerland; Hôpital Neuchâtelois, La Chaux-De-Fonds, Switzerland; Dept. of Intensive Care Medicine, Bern University Hospital, Switzerland; Prince of Wales, Hong Kong; Pamela Youde Nethersole Eastern Hospital, Hong Kong; Princess Margaret Hospital, Hong Kong; Nritld (Masih Daneshvari), Iran; Institute for Pulmonary Diseases of Vojvodina, Serbia; Hospital Health Center Kikinda, Serbia; KC Kragujevac, Serbia; Critical Care Department Attikon University Hospital, Athens, Greece; Hippokrateion General Hospital Thessaloniki, Greece; ICU Thriassio Hospital of Eleusis, Greece; Sanjay Gandhi Post Graduate Institute of Medical Sciences, India; Kerala Institute of Medical Sciences, India; Kaiser Franz Josef Spital Vienna, 1. Med, Austria; Medical University of Graz, Austria; Universitary Medical Center Nijmegen, Netherlands; Slingeland Ziekenhuis, Netherlands; Lund University Hospital, Sweden; THIVA, US, Linköping, Netherlands; Az Sint-Blasius, Belgium; Cliniques de l'Europe, Saint-Michel, Belgium; OUH, Svendborg Sygehus, Denmark; Hospital Materno Infantil-Caja Nacional de Salud, Bolivia; Clinical Center University Sarajevo, Bosnia and Herzegovina; Universidad Católica, Chile; Central Hospital of Mikkeli, Finland; Clinics of Kaunas University of Medicine, Lithuania; Fortis Clinique Darne, Mauritius; Centro Hospitalar Barreiro Montijo, Qatar; Trung Vuong Hospital, Viet Nam},
	abstract = {Introduction: Early use of corticosteroids in patients affected by pandemic (H1N1)v influenza A infection, although relatively common, remains controversial. Methods: Prospective, observational, multicenter study from 23 June 2009 through 11 February 2010, reported in the European Society of Intensive Care Medicine (ESICM) H1N1 registry. Results: Two hundred twenty patients admitted to an intensive care unit (ICU) with completed outcome data were analyzed. Invasive mechanical ventilation was used in 155 (70.5%). Sixty-seven (30.5%) of the patients died in ICU and 75 (34.1%) whilst in hospital. One hundred twenty-six (57.3%) patients received corticosteroid therapy on admission to ICU. Patients who received corticosteroids were significantly older and were more likely to have coexisting asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), and chronic steroid use. These patients receiving corticosteroids had increased likelihood of developing hospital-acquired pneumonia (HAP) [26.2% versus 13.8%, p < 0.05; odds ratio (OR) 2.2, confidence interval (CI) 1.1-4.5]. Patients who received corticosteroids had significantly higher ICU mortality than patients who did not (46.0% versus 18.1%, p < 0.01; OR 3.8, CI 2.1-7.2). Cox regression analysis adjusted for severity and potential confounding factors identified that early use of corticosteroids was not significantly associated with mortality [hazard ratio (HR) 1.3, 95% CI 0.7-2.4, p = 0.4] but was still associated with an increased rate of HAP (OR 2.2, 95% CI 1.0-4.8, p < 0.05). When only patients developing acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) were analyzed, similar results were observed. Conclusions: Early use of corticosteroids in patients affected by pandemic (H1N1)v influenza A infection did not result in better outcomes and was associated with increased risk of superinfections. associated with mortality [hazard ratio (HR) 1.3, 95% CI 0.7-2.4, p = 0.4] but was still associated with an increased rate of HAP (OR 2.2, 95% CI 1.0-4.8, p < 0.05). When only patients developing acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) were analyzed, similar results were observed. Conclusions: Early use of corticosteroids in patients affected by pandemic (H1N1)v influenza A infection did not result in better outcomes and was associated with increased risk of superinfections. © Copyright jointly held by Springer and ESICM 2010.},
