University Teaching Hospital; Lagos State University Teaching Hospital; Usmanu Danfodiyo University Teaching Hospital; National Orthopaedic Hospital Enugu; University of Calabar Teaching Hospital; University of Abuja Teaching Hospital; University of Uyo Teaching Hospital; Federal Medical Centre, Yenagoa; Seventh Day Adventist Hospital; Federal Medical Centre Birnin-Kebbi; Abia State University Teaching Hospital; Wesley Guild Hospital; Federal Medical Centre, Umuahia; University of Maiduguri Teaching Hospital; National Orthopaedic Hospital, Igbobi; University of Nigeria Teaching Hospital Enugu; Hospital Regional Docente de Trujillo, Peru; Hospital Nacional Hipolito Unanue; Mónica Pérez; Clinica Santa Ana; Hospital La Caleta; Hospital Nacional Sergio E Bernales; Hospital de Apoyo de Sullana; Hospital IV Essalud Huancayo; Hospital Nacional Arzobispo Loayza; Hospital Municipal Los Olivos; Hospital Jose Cayetano Heredia; Hospital Nacional Carlos Alberto Seguin Escobedo; Hospital Nacional Dos De Mayo; Hospital Nacional Cayetano Heredia; King Khalid University Hospital, Saudi Arabia; National Guard Hospital; Klinicki Centar Srbije, Serbia; National Neuroscience Institute, Singapore; FNsP Ružinov, Slovakia; NsP Poprad; NsP JA Reiman Hospital; Faculty Hospital F D Roosevelta; Dr George Mukhari Hospital, South Africa; George Provincial Hospital; Hospital Universitário Virgen del Roció, Spain; Hospital Ramón y Cajal de Madrid; Hospital Universitário Germans Trias i Pujol; Hospital Torrecardenas; Hospital Universitário Virgen de la Victoria; National Hospital of Sri Lanka, Sri Lanka; Muhimbili Orthopaedic Institute, Tanzania; Khon Kaen Regional Hospital, Thailand; Pattani Hospital; Suratthani Hospital; Bhumibol Adulyadej Hospital; Lampang Hospital; Rayong Hospital; Roi-Et Hospital; Phrae Hospital; Hospital Habib Thameur, Tunisia; University Hospital of North Staffordshire, United Kingdom; Royal London Hospital; Leicester Royal Infirmary; Nottingham University Hospitals NHS Trust; Frenchay Hospital; Countess of Chester Hospital; Hull Royal Infirmary; Royal Sussex County Hospital; Derby Hospitals NHS Trust; Bedford Hospital NHS Trust; Royal Liverpool University Hospital; Colchester General Hospital; Royal Lancaster Infirmary; Worthing Hospital; Darent Valley Hospital; Hope Hospital; Northern General Hospital; University Teaching Hospital, Lusaka, Zambia; Nchanga North General Hospital},
	abstract = {Background: Tranexamic acid can reduce bleeding in patients undergoing elective surgery. We assessed the effects of early administration of a short course of tranexamic acid on death, vascular occlusive events, and the receipt of blood transfusion in trauma patients. Methods: This randomised controlled trial was undertaken in 274 hospitals in 40 countries. 20 211 adult trauma patients with, or at risk of, significant bleeding were randomly assigned within 8 h of injury to either tranexamic acid (loading dose 1 g over 10 min then infusion of 1 g over 8 h) or matching placebo. Randomisation was balanced by centre, with an allocation sequence based on a block size of eight, generated with a computer random number generator. Both participants and study staff (site investigators and trial coordinating centre staff) were masked to treatment allocation. The primary outcome was death in hospital within 4 weeks of injury, and was described with the following categories: bleeding, vascular occlusion (myocardial infarction, stroke and pulmonary embolism), multiorgan failure, head injury, and other. All analyses were by intention to treat. This study is registered as ISRCTN86750102, Clinicaltrials.gov NCT00375258, and South African Clinical Trial Register DOH-27-0607-1919. Results: 10 096 patients were allocated to tranexamic acid and 10 115 to placebo, of whom 10 060 and 10 067, respectively, were analysed. All-cause mortality was significantly reduced with tranexamic acid (1463 [14·5%] tranexamic acid group vs 1613 [16·0%] placebo group; relative risk 0·91, 95% CI 0·85-0·97; p = 0·0035). The risk of death due to bleeding was significantly reduced (489 [4·9%] vs 574 [5·7%]; relative risk 0·85, 95% CI 0·76-0·96; p = 0·0077). Conclusion: Tranexamic acid safely reduced the risk of death in bleeding trauma patients in this study. On the basis of these results, tranexamic acid should be considered for use in bleeding trauma patients.},
